## Summary

Generalized the radial layout to support uneven, app-aligned window arcs with an overflow fisheye, changing **only** the level-1 windows ring (the apps ring is untouched).

**Core changes:**
- `Bringr/RadialLayout.swift` — Replaced the even N-division with an explicit per-slice arc table (`SliceArc`). `init(itemCount:)` reproduces the old equal layout exactly (back-compat lock); added `init(arcs:)`, `span(ofSliceAt:)`, and a `windowRing(windowCount:appCount:parentIndex:focusedWindowIndex:)` factory covering all three cases (tile / gap / fisheye) plus the single-app fallback. `hitTest` now uses modulo-2π arc containment, so arcs wrap the 12 o'clock seam and uncovered gaps return `nil`.
- `Bringr/RadialNavigator.swift` — `RadialRing` carries a stored `layout` shared by render and hit-test (can't desync). Added `focusedWindowIndex` + `focusWindowSlice(at:)` so the fisheye focus follows the hovered window live; `region(forOffset:)` returns the current `hovered` (a no-op) over an empty outer sector instead of collapsing.
- `Bringr/RadialMenuView.swift` — Reads `ring.layout` instead of building one.

**Tests:** 10 new `RadialLayout` geometry tests, a new `RadialNavigatorFisheyeTests` file (6 tests, wired into `project.pbxproj`), and a prehighlight-under-fisheye test.

**Quality gates:** `** BUILD SUCCEEDED **`, `swiftlint lint --strict` 0 violations, `xcodebuild test` 224/224 pass. App relaunched (PID 60390) and left running.

One caveat: the visual gate (verify the three cases on-screen) needs manual interaction — the wheel requires a live trigger + Accessibility permission — so I launched the app for you to confirm visually rather than claiming visual success.

